\layout Title

Number-Theoretic Series
\layout Author

Linas Vepstas <linas@linas.org> 
\layout Date

31 December 2004
\layout Abstract

A review of series that involve famous number-theoretic functions, such
 as the Moebius function, Euler's Totient, Liouville's function and the
 divisor functions.
 These all appear to have some sort of nascent modular-group symmetry waiting
 to be described.
\layout Abstract

A collection of miscellaneous constants related to various number-theortic
 functions, together with graphs of series involving number-theortic functions.
 
\layout Section

Number-Theortic Series
\layout Standard

Number-theortic series can arise in during the study of fractals.
 This paper reviews Maclaurin series of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}x^{n}$
\end_inset 

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are given by various well-known number number-theortic functions, such
 as Euler's Totient 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(n)$
\end_inset 

, the Moebius funtion 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(n)$
\end_inset 

, divisor functions and the like.
 No earth-shattering results are presented; rather, this is a survey intented
 to unveil the general shape of such sums.
 The results are for the most part numeric and consist primarily of graphs.
 
\layout Standard

Note that a general series of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $M(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}x^{n}$
\end_inset 

 with a radius of convergence of one can in general be converted to a Dirichlet
 series through integration: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}n^{-s}=\frac{1}{\Gamma(s)}\int_{0}^{\infty}t^{s-1}M(e^{-t})dt\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and conversly ...
